          "body": "Verses 3-7 catalog Manasseh's sins in escalating order, and the escalation is not accidental. He begins with the high places — already condemned but geographically distant from the temple. He then erects altars for Baal and an Asherah (echoing Ahab, the northern kingdom's benchmark apostate). Then he worships the host of heaven (astral religion from Mesopotamia). Then — and the historian marks this with special force by quoting God's own promise about the temple (21:4b) — he builds pagan altars inside the temple. Then he extends those altars into both temple courts (21:5). Finally, he installs a carved Asherah image inside the sanctuary itself (21:7), the inner space where God promised to put His name forever. The spatial logic of the catalog moves inward — from the hills of Judah to the holy of holies — so that by verse 7, Manasseh has penetrated the most sacred space in Israel with the most offensive foreign symbol. The historian's juxtaposition of God's promise ('I will put My name forever,' 21:7) with the Asherah image makes the desecration impossible to miss."
