          "body": "Verse 16 appears after the formal judgment oracle and functions as an addendum that intensifies the indictment beyond idolatry. Manasseh 'shed very much innocent blood until he had filled Jerusalem from one end to another.' The phrase *dam naqi* (innocent blood) is the legal category of blood-guilt that demands divine reckoning — Deuteronomy 19:10, Proverbs 6:17, and the prophets uniformly treat it as among the gravest possible covenant violations. Rabbinic tradition and later patristic commentary identify the innocent ones as faithful prophets and righteous individuals who refused to endorse Manasseh's apostasy — a reading that gains plausibility from the context of the anonymous prophets sent in 21:10 and from the parallel tradition in 2 Chronicles 33:10. 2 Kings 24:4 will later name Manasseh's innocent blood as the specific reason God refuses to forgive Judah even after Josiah's reform. The blood does not stay in chapter 21; it cries out through the remainder of the book."
